Cody is a coder, Roby is a robot. Cody provides instructions to Roby, who executes them.

The DYI Game CodyRoby Cody is a coder, Roby is a robot. Cody provides instructions to Roby, who executes them. Make unplugged coding the perfect DIY gift: no time, no cost, lot of fun, new skills. CodyRoby is a DIY card game to play with unplugged coding at any age. Download your free CodyRoby kit, print it out, cut the cards, fold the card box, and start playing! Instructions and represented by colourful cards reporting the symbols associated to three elementary instructions: move forward (green), turn left (yellow), turn right (red). Players act as Cody, using their cards to provide instructions to Roby, represented by a piece on the board. All the games can also be played on the floor, drawing a big board where kids can move plying the role of Roby. CodyRoby was invented on November 2014, to allow Italian schools to take part into the European Robotics Week at no cost. The kit can be dowloaded for free, printed out, cut-out and folded to compose the card deck, the board, the pieces and the box where everything fits. Since 2014 the kit has been distributed in many different versions, including those prepared for Europe Code Week, Africa Code Week and European Robotics Week. The color code adopted to make the three arrows easily recognizable has been adopted in the last two years by many other educational coding and robotics tools. The CodyRoby kit can be used in many different ways. Some of them are documented by short silent video tutorials, so that the basic rules can be learned by imitation and complemented by fantasy. But as soon as you start playing the proposed games, you can invent and play your own. In August 2016 the Starter Kit has been extended by introducing special cards representing loops and conditions. The new kit has been created for CodeMOOC and it is officially distributed for free on this page
The new kit provides a complete unplugged hour of code.

Activities On the web you'll find at least 10 different games that can be played with CodyRoby, and you can add and invent new ones. You can start from here:
  • CodeMOOC
  • CodeWeek
    • Note: Some written instructions are in italian, but there are also easy to follow silent videos to learn how to play.

The kit and the blocks The original paper kit can be printed and played alone. It's available here. If you want to add more "hardware" to the game (and make it stronger), you can print the items in this thing to add experience and interactivity You'll need to print:
  • 1 Board
  • 2-5 Robots
  • 24 Tiles
  • 6 Sensors
  • 8 Counters
  • 4+4 Targets
    • We suggest to print Sensors and Counters resized by 50% if you want to fit them on standard size paper cards.
• Coding
20 minutes, 1 hour or more

There is new v3 version !! Its nothing new just mirrored v2 design so shafts are on correct side same as on wheels :) so I suggest tu print now V3 version instead of v2 :)

Lets talk about this design and what motors chose:
This design use N20 motors that have metal gearing reduction.

  1. What speed ??
    Motors in all N20 spin with same speed and reduction change output speed but less output speed = more torque !!
    because motor spin with same speed on lower output speed motor need to make more turn to spin that and that generate more torque. I use 160 RPM because i like this speed :) On 300 RPM it would have less torque and more speed.

2.Less speed so it will stop easy ??
No, motors have good metal reduction and there are two motors so still if front wheels will block rear will still spin and that motors are used in RC winch so that is not easy to stop that by hand :)

  1. 6v or 12v ??
    That will depend on battery !! N20 motor will have full power on that voltage so if You plan to put 2S battery it will have max torque on 6v-8.4v and if You plan to use 3S battery it will have full power on 12v -12.6v But I think they all are designed on one voltage and that is 6v because this motor is small but I cant confirm that.

  2. Motors can spin in not synchronized speed ??
    Yes, because of not precise motors and some force for wheels mechanism it may spin in different speed. I don't care about that because for Me it's just a toy but if You want to fix that you can use two ESC (one for each motor) that will allow You to adjust speed when You connect it to separate channels and just clone signal from one to another channel (only on more advanced transmitters)

  3. If one motor will blocked second one will have more power ??
    Hard to say, someone say this would happen and all power will be transferred to spining motor like in differential. In My situation motors just keep spinning and car jumps trying to get on obstacle :D But to reduce that You can use separate ESC and both motors will have separate power

  4. 10A or 20A ESC ??
    Honestly ?? 5A :D I don't think this motors can draw more than 1A on stall each :D so no matter what You chose and also servo circuit can control it as well :D

  5. What is that yellow thing on motor ?? Do I need it ??
    Its ceramic capacitor 100nF (number 104) Brushed motors generate noise that may make servo nuts and this reduce that noise. It also work as a flywheel to reduce small voltage drops and make it work smooth. So do You need it ?? Not really !! All ESC have build in capacitors and servo have own capacitors but it's always good to add one on motors because capacitor on each side make it more stable. Someone say it keep power on same level and that may be true because capacitor work al a battery and store power but also capacity is so small that don't make difference when You turn motor off :D

I'm not NASA engineer so I may be wrong but this is how I understand this but if You want to add something here write that in comments.

title: Wylock Style Snap-together magnetic dungeon tiles

description.text:
Snap-together magnetic dungeon tiles. 1.25in (Wylock/TrueTiles style)

This design was inspired by calculuschild's top-locking dungeon tile remix and devonjones original work.

The biggest thing stopping me from making a ton of dungeon tiles: GLUE. Took far too long to glue these things together, and made a mess. Then I stumbled on calculuschilds design on reddit, and I HAD to have it. I printed out a good dozen of his design, but couldn't get them to snap together, they were always loose. I blame my printer for this, not the design. He made his around being able to swap out tiles base to base, which I didn't care about; I just wanted the simpler assembly. So I fired up Fusion and got to work, using his original clips as a baseline.

This is what I came up with. I increased the clip count to 1 on each corner, as I wasn't concerned about being able to swap tiles around. Added built-in supports (non-removable) to avoid unnecessary bridging. This also made it much stronger, which is important as the pressure needed to snap them together would break them off on the original design.

I can print 9 of the 2x2 in one print job. I churned out 4 runs of bases, and my first set of 9 floors were complete this morning. I had all 9 tiles assembled before the next batch had even begun printing!

  1. I've only printed one each of the 1x1 and 1x2. They're a bit more difficult to snap together.
  2. You CAN take these apart if needed. Slip something thin and sturdy (like a butter knife) between the base and floor and pry up. I've only done this a few times, and nothing has broken. YMMV

Current Issues:

  1. I had 2 of the locking pins break on me this morning. Unsure if printer, design, or print settings. Would love feedback from any that print these. I'm leaning towards the print setting here, as these bases I mass-printed were the first round I had 26 top layers on to get the pins solid.
  2. Sometimes the floors hang a bit above the base on one corner. My only thought here is the pins bent slightly. Would love some insight on this. Tiles still function fine this way.
  3. High resolution needed, at least for the pins. I've split the processes to print the pins at .1. The floors I printed at .3 just fine, but I may be able to fix some of my issues by printing at .1 instead.
  4. The overall height of the tiles likely doesn't match anything else out there.
  5. Less an issue and more of an FYI, but the 1x1 tiles WILL need pliers to snap together. You probably can't take these ones apart without breaking things.

Printer:

Custom

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

Mixed

Infill:

Your preference.

Notes:

If you're able to split layer heights on a model, you can print the bases .3 up until the locking pins. Print the locking pins at .1 I also increase my top solid layers for the pins to have the entire pin solid. 100% infill didn't work since that part is so small.

You may be able to get away with .3, but I had the best results this way.

My design skills are bad at best, so my floor tiles are super simple. I attempted to modify other tiles that had designs in them, however Fusion does not play well with complex imported STLs. Simple modifications take forever, crash Fusion, or simply wont work.

The snapping holes in the floor parts are larger than the pins. I accomplished this by making the pin larger on a duplicate base to use as a tool to cut the holes in the floor tile. They'd be impossible to snap together otherwise.

title: Snap cube, Kawai Joint, Interlocking, Math

description.text:
The snap cube is useful; the Kawai joint is mathematically appealing. I wondered, "Why not marry them in one design?" There you go: a 20mm^3 cube and Kawai joint (half a 20mm^3 cube) in one piece. They are designed to be fairly loose so children can assemble or disassemble them easily. There is a mirrored piece just in case you need some. A Kawai pair is also included to support more open-ended construction.

Obviously, the snap cubes allow rotation; the Kawai joints make rigid linear or perpendicular connections. Together, they support diverse constructions. Kids only know! So print a pile of them and leave them with some third or fourth graders and watch! Thanks for visiting.

I've remixed this Filament-Filter from hasings, here for the Creality-CR10. The idea to put filter + filament-guide in one part - now adapted with an axle to adjust dynamically the direction of the incomig filament: If the printed part is becoming higher and higher, the filament needs to change the angle coming from the reel to the input-hole of the filter. So this axle allows the filament to self-adapt to the needed angle.
Second: Change the filter-material now "online" - without extracting the filament from the extruder. So put the filament directly into the guide-hole between the two halfs of the filter, including two small sponges or folded pieces of soft-paper, then close the chamber with a piece of rubberband or a little zip-tie.
Hint: It is advisable to drill the inner-diameters of the axle to about 2,6mm (a bit more than 2,5) and the two screw-holes to about 3,2mm (a bit more than 3mm).

description.text:
This project is an entry for the MakerBot Giveaway competition announced on April 14th.
Enclosure Profiles are a simple way to design and make attractive custom enclosures for electronic and mechanical projects using today's modest resolution fabbers. The concept was inspired by classic pre-blobject radio and electronics enclosure designs like the Tivoli Model One and was originally intended to be used with aluminum extrusions in standard forms that could be cut to length like lumber. It was one of the proposed example design projects of the TMP2 Open Source Everything Project intended to illustrate the possibilities of globally refined open designs. However, the recent advent of personal fabbers like the MakerBot and RebRap offer the possibility of producing these enclosure profiles on-demand, printing them to length. 
Enclosure Profiles are 2D profile shapes that form the shape of a tubular enclosure finished by front and back faceplates. The profiles feature inner-surface slots or channels for the simple slide-in mounting of circuit boards or mechanical chassis plates and standoffs thus allowing a project assembly to be held together with just the faceplate screws and/or threaded rods. Faceplates are made from any useful flat stock material with openings cut to accommodate any desired controls, switches and buttons, displays, or interface ports. They can surface-mount to the enclosure profile ends or be mounted flush or recessed by routing the profile ends to make the necessary recess. 
Different perimeter profile shapes add additional features to the enclosure profiles, such as heat sink fins, stand-off legs, bases, or flanges for bolt attachment, and so on. By using stacked combinations of variant profile segments with the same inside profile and base dimensions and held together with threaded rods, it is possible to create more elaborate enclosures with different features. For instance, by combining a plain profile segment with two short segments with leg stand-off ridges one can make a case with four free-standing legs. Conversely, combining a large segment with stand-off ridges with two short plain segments makes a case with overhanging front and back bezels. 
An infinite variety of enclosures is possible by varying these simple 2D profile outlines with different dimensions, different combinations of interior slots/grooves, and different perimeter features and using them in different stacked combinations. The purpose of this design is to introduce viewers to this simple concept and encourage their own experimentation with different profiles of their own design. 
This concept will also work with laser/CNC cut flat sheet materials with multiple profile flats cut, stacked, and held together with threaded rods and surface-mount face plates. This approach will not produce a waterproof enclosure but does allow for the use of novel or recycled materials such as cardboard. 
The profile designs shown are several variants designed around the dimensions of the standard 170mm square Mini-ITX motherboard. This is intended for a fanless low-power PC enclosure with external power supply. Included are faceplate templates for surface-mount and flush/recessed faceplates. 
This author apologizes for the lack of a 3D view illustrating the profiles in extruded depth but, unfortunately, it was not possible to import these precision Illustrator drawings to SmartSketch for a quick rendering.

Note that this is an experimental design. Expect adjustments to suit differing hardware. It is recommended that thin test profiles or cardboard templates be made and compared to the intended insert boards and added components. 
This demonstration Enclosure Profile is designed as a fanless enclosure for a 170mm square Mini-ITX motherboard using external power supply. The profiles illustrated are for plain box, legged box, stacking box, and vertical standing base profiles. To use these profiles import them to the appropriate software for your fabber or other tools and print to the desired depth -in this case at least 200mm deep.
Use the faceplate templates to cut front and back faceplates. Most any material you wish can be used. The larger outer template is for surface mount faceplates. The smaller inner template is for flush/recessed faceplates and is also used as the routing template for these faceplates. The faceplates shown are blanks. Add template outlines for interface ports and vent grills as appropriate for your particular brand of motherboard. Note that these template screw holes and the screw/rod channels on the profiles are sized for M3 screws. The screw mount channels feature open channels for flexing and should accommodate self-threading screws of short length. Adjust these features as necessary for your choice of screws or threaded rods. 
To make profile combinations stacking profiles with different perimeter features, use the inner faceplate template as a routing guide for male and female profile edges. Fine adjustment is likely for this depending on your hardware and its precision. Likely combinations with this profile set would be adding short segments of the standing base or standoff ridge segments with a larger plain box segment. 
Following this Enclosure Profile example, one should be able to grasp the simple scheme behind this design concept and be able to invent custom enclosure profile designs in any desired size or shape. Simply modify the 2D outlines to devise your own custom enclosure shapes and print to depth. Comments and suggested improvements are welcome. Feel free to experiment and please share your new Enclosure Profile designs with others here on Thingverse.

This is a base to hold the Pawfly 5-Way Aquarium Air Flow Control Lever Valve Distributor Splitter available from many places, including: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B073CST36X

I modeled the valve set then subtracted it from a solid, making a socket. I set the top of the block just above the centerline of the horizontal pipe, so that it clicks in to place for a solid friction fit.

對於作品還蠻滿意的，我覺得很可愛！但有幾顆章魚燒的咖啡色醬料有點太小片，而且因為時間有點緊迫，所以白色美乃滋的粗細沒有搓得很均勻，看起來就沒有那麼精緻。

請描述從黏土到建模時，你在設計上的修正（可能是小部份或是置換大主題） 我沒有辦法將醬料做成不規則形，所以改成簍空的半圓球蓋在圓球上。彎彎曲曲的美乃滋更沒有辦法，只能用社群造型產生器的s wall，但我不知道要怎麼讓它貼合在圓球上，造成一個懸空的現象。 tinkerCAD軟體的哪一項功能最吸引你？讓你感到驚艷？ 360度都能旋轉，能清楚檢查有沒有穿幫的地方；特色造型產生器和社群造型產生器裡面有很多很複雜的圖形，解決了很多製作上的困難。 在你的設計作品中，描述一個最複雜的結構，並試圖描述它是由哪些向量幾合構成的？ 最複雜的應該是半圓球簍空的醬料部分(因為美乃滋作失敗……) 拉出兩個半圓球，把其中一個的高度和長寬都拉大，沒有放大的那個則從「實體」設為「孔」，兩個疊在一起之後再群組在一起，就得到簍空的半圓球了。 3D列印的生活應用層面，試圖以醫療、建築、和教育三大面向給予描述。 醫療：已經普遍用於牙科、外科、復健科，目前的3D列印醫學應用主要以手術輔助、手術修補物、輔具製作為主(例如上下顎、手骨、牙齒)，未來可望朝向器官移植、器官3D列印之方向發展。 建築：不同於常見的小型3D列印製作，大規模的3D列印有一些很實際的應用方法：以救災來說，當龍捲風或地震損毀公共建設，使上千個民眾無家可歸，3D列印機就能用來快速重建橋樑、道路。 教育：3D 印表機是一種同時擁有視覺和觸覺的學習方式，具有很強的誘惑力，在觸覺學習中，學生不是在黑板或顯示器上簡單地看文字或圖形，而是通過他們的觸覺抓住核心概念的三維模型，這樣能夠吸收和消化知識，使學生不再遺忘所學的課程。 給大家一個印下來的理由吧（投票） 我覺得我的作品不適合印下來，因為我的美乃滋沒有貼合球面，有部分是懸空的。

description.text:
This is a prototype light base for growing phytoplankton.

To complete the project you will need both items printed, and may need to print the disc to use as a pattern for trimming a piece of 1/4" clear acrylic to make the lens.

Suggested parts:
Microswitch: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00DN7Z67E
Grow LED string: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00XHRYX2O
DC Jacks: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01GO56CCE
Power supply: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B073ZF19QV

I also used a 5 ohm, 5 watt power resistor inline to dial down the LED current to around a half amp, to keep it from getting too hot.

I've not yet started my Phytoplankton grow operation for my reef tank, so I don't yet know if I'll need more or less light to get a good culture going.

Update: I can now confirm that 6.6 watts of red/blue grow LEDs does a great job with 1 liter flasks. I'm getting good growth, and need to split each flask once a week. (100ml phyto to 900ml new water, with 1ml f/2.) The box does get warm, I would not recommend using in a hot area or with any more light than 6 watts without making vents.

I have a second version in the works that uses an aluminum PCB for the 1W LEDs, and has some ventilation that should give me more light, with less heat retention in the case.

This is a completely fake tank and is based on the original model created by modeler Brian Fowler in 1997. So it is not something that even came close to being real. But it is a fun thing to produce and can be used to stir up an internet discussion or frighten your opponents with.

A word of warning. This is a big model with a lot of components and will consume a lot of filament and time. The hull is just over 11inches (28cm) long.

Like the original model this design is a Frankenstein’s monster of parts from a number of other tanks. Apart from the KV-1s there are turrets from a T60 and a BT-7 as well as the Katyusha.

I had to split the hull into three pieces so that it would fit on the build plate of my printer.

Gun barrels should be printed horizontally, I used the “touching build plate” support option in Cura.

You will need one of each piece except the deck turrets, of which four are needed. Print as many of the stowage items as you think you will need. Or you can make use of TigerAce’s Stowage pack.

The three hull pieces will need cleaning up before being glued together

The Tower and tower with turret are completely optional, and provide the vehicle with the ability to hide behind something, like a small ural, and still be able to spot targets for it’s weapons. The quickest option is to print just the tower, clip off the base place and then glue or place it on top of the “midships’ turret. Printing the “Tower with Turret” option will take longer but is more robust.

Good printing and good luck.

Due to a mechanical problem, I changed the differential and the ratio is different. I have a greater acceleration but a lower top speed! I had to change a gear on the rotating speedometer cable, engine side.
It is apparently very hard to find. I tried some without good result. My friend said it was not available. Then I measured my speed with a GPS and compared. When I was 50 km/h, the meter reading 60. The number of kilometers traveled also increased faster. I had to slow the rotating cable with a factor 1.2.
This piece, once seated behind the counter, allows a correct speed display

Print parts and test gears. smooth axes until everything goes well without jolts. I used PLA. No need support. Put a lot of grease. Close with 3 countersunk screw M3 and 3 nuts  
For the tip (the little bar that goes into the counter), I had the best result with nylon. PLA broke and Bendlay was frayed. You need to slightly whittle it fits well in the gear and the meter. You can also use a metallic square profile and a file.  
Put the gear housing in place and secure with the fixing. Turn the gear housing so that the rotatable cable connects straight as possible. There is enough room behind the counter.

description.text:
KV-IV Fake Tank (1/100)

1/100 scale version

This is a completely fake tank and is based on the original model created by modeler Brian Fowler in 1997. So it is not something that even came close to being real. But it is a fun thing to produce and can be used to stir up an internet discussion or frighten your opponents with.

A word of warning. This is a big model with a lot of components and will consume a lot of filament and time.

Like the original model this design is a Frankenstein’s monster of a vehicle with parts from a number of other tanks. Apart from the KV-1s there are turrets from a T60 and a BT-7 as well as the Katyusha.

Gun barrels should be printed horizontally, I used the “touching build plate” support option in Cura.

You will need one of each piece except the deck turrets, of which four are needed. Print as many of the stowage items as you think you will need. Or you can make use of TigerAce’s Stowage pack.

If you check out the 1/56 scale version of this model, there is the option of an observation tower on top of the middle turret. I have not managed to print a tower I am happy with yet. But if you want to have a go, scale down the 1/56 version to 56% size. The Tower and tower with turret are completely optional, and provide the vehicle with the ability to hide behind something, like a small ural, and still be able to spot targets for it’s weapons. The quickest option is to print just the tower, clip off the base place and then glue or place it on top of the “midships’ turret. Printing the “Tower with Turret” option will take longer but is more robust.

Good printing and good luck
For a few giggles I have created a stats sheets for Bolt Action

This is my attempt at a case for the very excellent QRP Labs QCX transceiver. I'm very new to this so maybe you can improve on the design.

The design criteria was to case a QCX that had been built to the manual with the controls all mounted on the board. I didn't want to be constrained by a square box and shaft extensions. The only concession is two extensions for the tact switches.

An optional print is a shim to convert the supplied pot to be suitable for a grub screw. I found the shaft tended to deform and make the control eccentric.

The gain control recess prints badly on my printer. I use some heavy weigh supports here but still get a rough surface that needs some finishing. Tips welcome! SEE BELOW

Screws are M3 x 20mm (6 off). Currently these self tap into the top case parts. A better solution would be to use brass inserts.

A word of warning! Due to the nature of the QCX layout everything is very tight with virtually no tolerance in places. Keep all components close to the board - in particular the hairpin resistors should be bent as close as possible to the resistor body to save height. Having said all that, mine fitted without a problem.

description.text:
Extend your flight time from 4 minutes to 8 minutes. My design hides wings under the cover that pop out when the throttle is released. Its smooth gliding until you start the motors again at which time the wings pop back inside the cover.

Its all done automatically so there's little to fiddle with. At high speeds the sleek wings should sustain flight.

A 6V mini servo is connected in the center of the cover and pulls or pushes the wings open or closed.

No rudder on this craft. To turn simply use the standard controls, the props do the rest.

With hidden wings the arrow dynamics of the drone stay intact until you want to glide again.

This is a concept that needs a lot of tuning. Had some help from fellow designers... Thanks.

A simple laser cut desktop mail organizer using no glue or fasteners. This design accomodates various size letters and packages on the reconfigurable horizontal shelves, and the top verticle slots hold mail vertically to signify outgoing postage. The vertical nature of the "mail out" top is meant to evoke the vertical mailbox flag. There is also a fun leaning and flexing motion incorporated in this design, as mail is added the organizer tilts and flexes in response to how the user adds mail. Be sure to size width of joinery cuts to thickness of wood being used.

Starting with laser-cut "mailbox" ideation sketches I explored various opportunities before ultimately proceeding with this design. I then made this in SolidWorks as a next step, this model was then exported as drawings and converted to .ai files for laser cutting. I designed something with which the component parts would "nest" in their layout to maximize the strengths of the laser cutting process and be as efficient with material as possible.

title: Easy Spool Holder slightly tweaked (Prusa MK2 / MK2S / MK3)

description.text:
I really like the original design by IsmaelPR1 as found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1768975

It must have costed him quite some time to design this. Also the integrated filament guide is great. I printed the original design and found that it takes quite some time to print the bolts as well as the spool holder with the integrated filament guide. It takes quite some time because it is printing predominantly in the Z-direction and considering cooling, printing slows down. In addition it is does not give the strongest results either. Since I also use filament filters on each roll of filament, I had to cut the filament guide such that I can insert the filament without taking off the filament filter.

Hence several months ago I designed some improvements, left it for a while and recently was able to print it and made some further improvements. Now I am sharing these:

This remix has a separate filament guide which prints more in the X/Y direction (since its lying on the bed) and hence prints faster and is much stronger. The filament guide is attached to the right spool holder support element by an M3 bolt (you use a spare bolt from the Prusa spare parts kit) or by gluing it (if printed in ABS it can be glued by Acetone). I added two 45 degree recesses in the filament guide; you can either choose to leave the filament guide in one piece, or quickly make a small cut with a saw or sharp knife such that you can just insert the filament through the saw cut.

In addition, the original bolts had threading over the entire length which is not needed either. Therefor I made a rod with only threading at both end-sides of the rods and also these rods can be printed horizontally lying on the bed and as a result can be printed faster and are stronger. Added some newly designed nuts as well just for the looks.

Furthermore I ran some cables on backside of the top of the frame for my lights and made some recesses in the main spool support elements, such that cables can be guided between these holders and the frame.

For the rest no changes, so you need to grab the other components (spool rolers) from the original post (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1768975)

Kudos to IsmaelPR1 for designing and sharing this great design.

Update: also quickly drafted a "spool lock" to keep very light (sample) spools in place on the Easy Spool Holder. For details see here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2663667

I got tired of cracking open libraries that I wrote and trying to decipher the comments and documentation that I left for myself. Instead, I thought it would be nice if I could just use <./path/to/library> and then call help_libraryName() to get a list of the available functions and module calls.

This is an attempt to add a standardized way of documenting modules.

The current version will be hosted on Git Hub: https://github.com/txoof/module_help

Add the module help_YourLibraryNameHere() {} to your OpenSCAD library to provide some
callable help.

Usage from an imported library:
//provide a list of all help topics in the "colors" library:

use <./libraries/colors.scad>
help_colors();

//output:
ECHO: "Available Help Topics in this Library:"
ECHO: "colorArray"
ECHO: "chord"
ECHO: "RGB"
ECHO: "RGBScale"
ECHO: "red"
ECHO: "redScaled"

//get help on a particular topic from the "colors" library:
help_colors("colorAray");

//output:
ECHO: "Help for module/function: colorArray"
ECHO: "function: colorAray(columns = <integer>, rows = <integer, scaled = <boolean>)"
ECHO: "returns: <vector of vectors>"
ECHO: "Description: returns column X rows vector of interpolated RGB values"
ECHO: "Paramaters:"
ECHO: "     columns      <integer>   1-255 columns"
ECHO: "     rows         <integer>   1-255 rows"
ECHO: "     scaled       <boolean>   scale the colors from white to full color"

The model library included below requires a library name and a vector containing specific
help information. See the examples below:

//Examples

LibraryName = "Name of your library";

modules = [
           ["nameOfModuleOrFunction", //callable name of module
            // module/function: callable name of function (paramater1 = <data type>)
            "module: nameOfModuleOrFunction(param1 = <data type>"),
            //returns: description of return OR none (module)
            "returns: none (module)",
            //description of function
            "Description: This module does things",
            //Paramaters: - list of paramaters, data types and an explanation of use
            "Paramaters: ",
            //paramater one
            "     radius        <real>      radius of bolt head"
            //paramter two
            "     number        <integer>   number of objects to draw"
           ], //following modules can be described using the same format
          ];
